Studio courses, which serve as the basis of training for architectural practice, show notable conservatism over time, while seminar and lecture offerings vary like humanities departments. gsx$paragraph-text.$t: Architecture, a hybrid discipline combining aesthetics and engineering, is a distinctive case. Studio courses, which serve as the basis of training for architectural practice, show notable conservatism over time, while seminar and lecture offerings vary like humanities departments. It's in the latter courses that architects cultivate style and sensibility and learn to approach their work as historically-informed artists and critical interpreters of human uses of the built environment.

Unique and new courses pop up throughout the period of our data, reflecting remarkable invention and transformation over time. Again, this ripple echoes patterns we see in the humanities. At the same time, it also likely reflects the distinctive nature of the faculty in architecture, comprised of professional practitioners who come and go more frequently, infusing the curriculum with new viewpoints and enthusiasms.

content.$t: paragraph-id: 0, snippet-id: 0, paragraph-title: Transcript Stories of Eliot & Stein, paragraph-text: It's safe to say that, if you wanted to grow up to author "The Wasteland" and Four Quartets, you could hardly do better than to follow the course of study young Thomas Stearns Eliot. His undergraduate course hewed rigorously, almost exclusively, to languages and literatures. In his freshman and sophomore years, he took courses in French, German, and Greek, adding the history of ancient art and the history of philosophy in his second year. Eliot's history of modern philosophy course, Phil B2, was taught by George Santayana, the famous aphorist, critic of German idealism, and explicator of pragmatism. In his senior year, Eliot would take a second course, philosophy of history, with Santayana as well. Beyond this, Eliot's focus remained rigorously trained on literature and aesthetics as an upperclassmen, with course in English literature in its relation to the continent, tendencies in continental literature of the renaissance, Latin literature, and the history of allegory., clustering: subjectDescription, data-link: ./data/story-stein-eliot/ts-eliot-1960-2020_subjectDescription.json, new-dataset: TRUE, highlighted: FALSE

paragraph-id: 6, snippet-id: 6, paragraph-text: A century after he completed his studies, Eliot's signal in the curriculum is scarcely wider than his own course of study. Eliot's appearance in courses betokens both his centrality in the modern canon, and the narrowness of his impact and appeal. Beyond a consistent murmur in survey courses in the English Department, Eliot's presence is notable in courses plumbing connections between literature and religion—reflecting the intense focus of his graduate study, and the rigorous, rich, tortured piety of his later work., clustering: subjectDescription, data-link: ./data/story-stein-eliot/ts-eliot-1960-2020_subjectDescription.json, new-dataset: FALSE, highlighted: TRUE
